     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ INTRODUCTION ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Intro "Introduction"

 NNTP is a news client for the Amiga, which collects usenet news from a
news server using the NNTP protocol. ( see RFC 977 )

 The server must support the @{"XOVER" link Xover} command (I think most do..).

Conditions of use:

 1) I accept no liabilty for any mishaps/bugs whatsoever.

 2) Not for commercial use. @{"Contact me" link Feedback} if you wish to distribute NNTP
    on a commercial basis.

Features:

 o Powerful (and @{b}FAST!@{ub}) killfiling.
   You'll never have to download massive unwanted binaries again.
   You can also kill boring/offensive people/subjects/sites/xposts.

 o Reliable. Doesn't crash in the event of long headers/unusual msgid's
   etc... In fact, it doesn't crash @{b}period@{ub}. (touch wood.. ;)

 o Efficient. Latency minimised through intelligent design and fairly
   sophisticated queueing. ie Faster collection, and less spent on funding
   your local telecom paras^H^H^H^H provider.

 o Informative display of progress, so you can see exactly what's
   going on at all stages.

 o All kills are logged, both to provide feedback and to allow subsequent
   article retrieval if desired.

 o Low maintenance. NNTP doesn't use timestamps, or a history file.
   i.e. no need to trim the "newshistory" every so often...

 o Low stack requirements - the standard 4096 is just fine...

 o Cheap. This program is pay-what-you-like-ware, written in the full
   knowledge that most of you would like to pay nothing at all. ;-)

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ INSTALLING ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Install "Installing NNTP"

 Installation of NNTP is very simple and it can be run alongside your
existing news client if you wish to test it first - simply run it but
don't bother unbatching the news.

 You can either keep the executable and other files in one drawer, or
place them wherever you feel is suitable. The everything-in-one-drawer
approach is probably best while you're trying it out.

 Before you use NNTP for the first time, you'll need to copy/edit the
@{"example nntp.cfg" LINK "nntp.cfg/MAIN"} to reflect your own preferences.

 See @{"Configuration" link Config} for details on how to configure NNTP.

 Finally, you may well wish to make an alias/script to call NNTP so
that you don't have to type all the CLI options (as detailed in @{"Usage" link Usage})
every time.

 AmiTCP-DIS users may want to look at a few @{"notes" link amitcpdis} about using NNTP
with this particular package.

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ AMITCP-DIS ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node amitcpdis "Notes for users of AmiTCP-DIS"

 Users of the AmiTCP-DIS archive, a package geared around customers of
Demon Internet in the UK, may find the following notes helpful when moving
from the news system used to NNTP.

 NNTP is an ideal replacement for the commonly-used 'NNTPClient' and
eliminates all the common bugs and problems associated with this program,
as well as adding vastly improved killfiling!

-  Firstly, NNTP can be used completely in place of NNTPClient.  It is
  likely you'll never want to go back to NNTPClient after using NNTP! :)

-  The file UULib:Newsgroups is @{b}not@{ub} used by NNTP to determine
  which newsgroups you wish to read. The newsgroup list is contained in
  nntp.cfg. However, depending on your choice of newsreader you may still
  need to maintain UULib:Newsgroups with a current list of newsgroups.
   Some newsreaders, including Tin and GRn, will read their newsgroup list
  from this file, and in addition TrimNews (which expires articles) will
  take the newsgroup names and expiry dates from this file.

-  You'll probably want to replace AmiTCP:bin/nntptransfer with a script
  file which calls NNTP.  This script is the one which gets called by
  default when you link up with news collection enabled.  Alternatively,
  modify AmiTCP:bin/link and change the call to nntptransfer to a call to
  NNTP.

-  You may also need to modify the call to DanNews (or whichever news
  unbatcher you use) so that it knows where to look for the batch file
  which NNTP creates.  This call is normally found in the nntptransfer
  script.

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ CONFIGURING ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Config "Configuring NNTP"

 Configuration of NNTP is done via a config file. An @{"example nntp.cfg" link "nntp.cfg/MAIN"}
file is supplied, which you can modify appropriately.

   @{bg fill} Mandatory Commands: @{bg back}

   @{" ServInfo " link ServInfo} - Technical details about your news server

   @{bg fill} Optional CLI-equivalent Commands: @{bg back}

   @{"   Host   " link Opt_CLI} - Specify your news server
   @{"    Dat   " link Opt_CLI} - Specify the dat filename.
   @{"  Batch   " link Opt_CLI} - Specify the batch filename.
   @{"    Log   " link Opt_CLI} - Specify the log filename.

   @{bg fill} Newsgroup Information: @{bg back}

   @{"  Group   " link Group} - Subscribe to a newsgroup

   @{bg fill} Killing unwanted articles: @{bg back}

   @{"   Subj   "  link Opt_Subj} - Kill using subject field
   @{"   From   "  link Opt_From} - Kill using author field
   @{"  MsgID   " link Opt_MsgID} - Kill using Message-ID field

   @{"   Kill   "      link Kill} - Simple @{"XOVER" link Xover} substring kill

   @{bg fill} Optional commands: @{bg back}

   @{"  Plain   "     link Plain} - Use simpler form of output
   @{"   SAFE   "      link SAFE} - Operate in "safe" mode.
   @{"    END   "       link END} - Indicates end of the configuration file.

 You can insert comments into the file using ';' or '#'.

 Any errors in the config file will be reported when you attempt
to run the program.

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ SERVINFO ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node ServInfo "NNTP configuration commands: ServInfo"

The ServInfo command indicates where to find the:

Message-Id:
Bytes:
Lines:
From:
Subject:

information in the @{"XOVER" link Xover} line for each article.

 For most servers, this should be: ServInfo "4,6,7,2,1"

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ Opt_CLI ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Opt_CLI "CLI equivalent commands."

 Syntax:
 
   Host "your.news.server"  - The address of your news server.
   Dat  "filename"          - Path to your dat file
 Batch  "filename"          - Path to your newsbatch file
   Log  "filename"          - Path to your logfile

nb These can all be overruled if the corresponding CLI argument is used.
See @{"Usage" LINK Usage}.

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ GROUP ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Group "NNTP configuration commands: Group"

 The 'Group' command is used to list the newsgroups you want to read and
also defines limits on article size. It is formatted as follows:

@{i}Group "<Group Name>" <Max Lines> <Max Bytes>@{ui}

Group Name:  The full name of the newsgroup e.g. demon.ip.support.amiga
Max Lines:   The maximum allowable lines in an article.  Typically a value
             of 300-400 should allow any 'real' articles through whilst
             blocking spam.

Max Bytes:   The maximum allowable bytes in an article.  A value of
             around 30000-40000 should kill most binaries whilst allowing
             normal articles through.

@{b}eg:@{ub} Group "demon.ip.support.amiga" 400 40000

 nb If you don't want to limit the number of lines/bytes, set the
corresponding value to 0.

@{b}eg:@{ub} Group "comp.sys.amiga.misc" 0 30000

 This would kill any article in this group larger than 30000 bytes in
size, but with no limits on the no. of lines.

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ Opt_Subj ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Opt_Subj "Field specific kills: Subj"

 i) @{i} Subj "*some*pattern*" @{ui} (Case Sensitive)
 
ii) @{i} SUBJ "*some*pattern*" @{ui} (CASE INSENSITIVE)

 If "*some*pattern*" matches the Subject: field, the article will be killed.

 This is one of the better ways of killing spam/velveeta.
Some favourite subject kills of mine are:

SUBJ "*make*fast*"
SUBJ "http://*"

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ Opt_From ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Opt_From "Field specific kills: From"

 i) @{i} From "*some*pattern*" @{ui} (Case Sensitive)
 
ii) @{i} FROM "*some*pattern*" @{ui} (CASE INSENSITIVE)

 If "*some*pattern*" matches the From: field, the article will be killed.

 A typical From: field looks like this:

Orinoco A. Womble <womble@wimbledon.com>

 So, you could use:

From "*womble@wimbledon.com*" 	; Standard, fairly specific kill.
FROM "*orinoco*womble*"		; Using name instead of email addr.
FROM "*@wimbledon.com*"		; Would kill the whole domain...


@{b}PLEASE NOTE:@{ub}

 The leading and trailing asterisks ('*'s) in 'From' and 'MsgId' kills are
quite important and it is extremely likely that you will want to include
them. The reason for this is illustrated by a typical From: line...

From: Mr Nuisance <nuisance@annoying.com>

 In this case, a kill using the command:

@{i}From "*@annoying.com"@{ui} or @{i}From "*nuisance@annoying.com"@{ui}

will NOT kill the article since the From line has a '>' following the
e-mail address.  So you would normally wish to use:

@{i}From "*@annoying.com*"@{ui} or @{i}From "*nuisance@annoying.com*"@{ui}

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ Opt_MsgID ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Opt_MsgID "Field specific kills: MsgID"

 i) @{i} MsgID "*some*pattern*" @{ui} (Case Sensitive)
 
ii) @{i} MSGID "*some*pattern*" @{ui} (CASE INSENSITIVE)

 If "*some*pattern*" matches the Message-ID: field, the article will
be killed.

 This is sometimes a good way to kill a domain.

eg:

 MSGID "*@savetrees.com*"

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ KILL ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Kill "NNTP configuration commands: Kill"

 The 'Kill' command allows simple kills.  It has the following format:

@{i}Kill "<substring to kill on>"@{ui}

 Technical info - simple killing is done by simply looking for matches
in the @{"XOVER" link Xover} information for each article.

@{b}Example:@{ub} Kill "Monday"

 This will kill any article containing the string "Monday" in it's
@{"XOVER" link Xover} string. eg Articles posted on a Monday, Subjects containing the
word "Monday" etc etc...

 Why you'd want to do such a thing is a different matter, a Boomtown Rats
fan perhaps ?

 My main use for this command is to kill crossposts by matching entries
in the Xref field. eg  Kill "alt.flamewars:"

 The 'Kill' command can be used in two ways - case sensitive or case
insensitive.  Calling the command with 'KILL' will ignore the case of the
string, whereas calling it with 'Kill' will only kill strings which match
*exactly* (case included).

 One more point, if the @{"XOVER" link Xover} data is too long (> 4K), the article will
automatically be killed. Usually this is because either the Xref: or
References: header is huge.

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ PLAIN ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Plain "nntp.cfg optional commands: PLAIN"

 If used, this command makes NNTP generate a slightly simpler form of
output, more suitable to redirecting to a file. See @{"sample output" LINK Sample_Output}
 ie No ansi codes are used for progressive counts etc.


( Personally I prefer this switched on, even when displaying the output
in a shell window. Try it with and without to see what suits your
tastes. )

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ SAFE ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node SAFE "nntp.cfg optional commands: SAFE"

 The default behaviour is to tag each message as collected as it is
*queued* (not collected). This behaviour means that NNTP avoids getting
"stuck" in the event of an unforseen problem.

 Some people however prefer to minimise the chance of articles being
lost, and if you fall into this category, you'll want to use the SAFE
option. This command prevents any changes to the nntp.dat file in
the event of an error, ie if an error occurs, it's as if the whole
session never happened. (Though you'll have some articles collected in
the batch file, and kills logged.)

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ END ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node END "nntp.cfg optional commands: END"

 Instructs NNTP to finish examining the cfg file at this point.

@endnode

