     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ XOVER ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node xover "NNTP technical info: XOVER"

 XOVER is one of the NNTP eXtension commands. It allows a news client
to grab a small parcel of information about each article, enabling
killing/filtering without the overhead of scanning the entire header/
body.

 The following is an excerpt from:
http://ds.internic.net/internet-drafts/draft-ietf-nntpext-imp-00.txt

[
    Each line of output will be formatted with the article number,
    followed by each of the headers in the overview database or the
    article itself (when the data is not available in the overview
    database) for that article separated by a tab character.  The
    sequence of fields must be in this order: subject, author,
    date, message-id, references, byte count, and line count. Other
    optional fields may follow line count.
]
    
 Assuming your news server complies with this, then you should use the
following Servinfo argument.

ServInfo "4,6,7,2,1"

 Where the fields are {Message-ID,Bytes,Lines,From,Subject} respectively.

@endnode

     [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[ USAGE ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

@node Usage "Using NNTP"

NNTP needs to be called from the CLI. It's template is as follows:

@{i} CFG/K,HOST/K,DAT/K,BATCH/K,LOG/K,NG=NEWGROUPS/K @{ui}

 It's probably easiest to use a script, then you can automatically grab
the news, unbatch it/gate it into a Fido packet, whatever. For use with
a UUCP or UUCP-style system, you may want to use some program such as
DanNews (see http://www.ramjam.demon.co.uk/software/) to unbatch the news
files created by NNTP.

@{u}Description of arguments@{uu}

  CFG=   path to your config file
         default - progdir:nntp.cfg

 HOST=   address of the news server @{b}e.g.@{ub} "news.demon.co.uk"


  DAT=   path to file used to store newsgroup data
         default - progdir:nntp.dat

BATCH=   path to newsbatch file (holds collected articles).
         default - progdir:Newsbatch

  LOG=   path to file used for logging kills.
         default - progdir:nntp.log

   NG=   (or NEWGROUPS=) Optional file to append any new newsgroup
         names to.

 nb. Specifying the HOST,DAT,BATCH & LOG arguments can be done both via
the CLI, and in the cfg file. In the event of a conflict, CLI arguments
take precedence.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

  (i) NNTP CFG=home:nntp.cfg NG=AmiTCP:new_newsgroups.doc

 (ii) NNTP CFG=home:nntp.cfg HOST=news.demon.co.uk DAT=home:NNTPData
BATCH=uuspool:newsbatch LOG=home:nntp.log NG=uuspool:.newgroups

 In (i) the HOST,DAT,LOG,BATCH arguments are specified in the cfg file
itself.

 The first time you ever run NNTP, or the first time you run it after
deleting the dat file, no news will be collected.  From thereon, each
time you run it, all new news (i.e. news available on the server since
your last download) will be collected.

  The "dat" file is where newsgroup information is stored, such as
the last article collected from each group. (Max limit of 256 groups).
If you delete the dat file, you'll start afresh and a new dat file
will be created. (If you're a cautious soul, you may wish to make
occasional backups of this file "just in case...")

 As NNTP is running, it will output lots of information to the CLI and
the news collected will be stored into the batch file.

 If a batch file with the pathname you have specified already exists,
new news will be appended to the end of it. ie You will not lose any
news by running NNTP twice in succession without unbatching inbetween.

@endnode

